16 STUDY LOCAL GOVERNMENT BUDGET AND FISCAL CONTROL ACT
17 SECTION 6.5.(a) Study. – The State and Local Government Finance Division of
18 the Department of State Treasurer shall study and report on the need to update Article 3 of
19 Chapter 159 of the General Statutes, The Local Government Budget and Fiscal Control Act. In
20 making recommendations, the study shall consider all of the following:
21 (1) Existing statutory complexity and inconsistencies.
22 (2) The ability for local government to comply with statutory requirements in
23 light of the shortage of qualified local government finance professionals.
24 (3) The need for training of local staff and local elected officials.
25 (4) Enforcement gaps in current statutory language.
26 (5) How to address the varying financial management challenges faced by
27 governments of varying sizes.
28 SECTION 6.5.(b) Consultation. – In conducting this study, the Division shall
29 consult with the North Carolina League of Municipalities, the North Carolina Association of
30 County Commissioners, the UNC School of Government, the North Carolina Government
31 Finance Officers Association, and at least two executive branch agencies that interact directly
32 with local governments on financial matters, of which one must be the Department of
33 Environmental Quality.
34 SECTION 6.5.(c) Report. – No later than January 31, 2027, the Division shall submit
35 an initial report of its findings to the chairs of the House Finance Committee, the Senate Finance
36 Committee, the House Committee on State and Local Government, and the Senate Committee
37 on State and Local Government. No later than October 1, 2027, the Division shall submit a final
38 report of its findings, including any recommendations for statutory changes, to the chairs of the
39 House Finance Committee, the Senate Finance Committee, the House Committee on State and
40 Local Government, and the Senate Committee on State and Local Government.
41
42 MODIFY GENERAL ASSEMBLY ACTUARIAL NOTE PROCEDURE
43 SECTION 6.6. G.S. 120-114 reads as rewritten:
44 "§ 120-114. Actuarial notes; Retirement System cost estimates.
45 …
46 (b) The author of each bill or resolution shall present a copy of the bill or resolution, with
47 his request for an actuarial note, to the Fiscal Research Division which shall have the duty to
48 prepare said actuarial note as promptly as possible. Actuarial notes shall be prepared and
49 transmitted to the author or authors no later than two weeks after the request for the actuarial note
50 is made, unless an extension of time is agreed to by the author or authors as being necessary in
51 preparation of the note. Any person who signs an actuarial note knowing it to contain false
House Bill 1126-Third Edition Page 45

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 information shall be fined not more than five hundred dollars ($500.00) or imprisoned not more
2 than six months, or both.
3 …
4 (e) At any time any committee of either house reports any legislative instrument, to which
5 an actuarial note or notes are attached at the time of committee consideration, with any
6 amendment of such nature as would substantially affect the cost to or the revenues of any
7 retirement system, or program of hospital, medical, disability, or related benefits for teachers and
8 State employees, as stated in the actuarial note or notes attached to the measure at the time of
9 such consideration, it shall be the responsibility of the chairman of the committee reporting such
10 instrument to obtain from the Fiscal Research Division actuary employed by the system or
11 program an actuarial note of the fiscal and actuarial effect of the change proposed by the
12 amendment reported. Such actuarial note shall be attached to the report of the committee on the
13 measure as a supplement thereto. A floor amendment to a bill or resolution to which an actuarial
14 note was attached at the time of committee consideration of the bill or resolution shall not be in
15 order, if the amendment affects the costs to or the revenues of a retirement system, or program
16 of hospital, medical, disability, or related benefits provided for teachers and State employees,
17 unless the amendment is accompanied by an actuarial note, prepared by the Fiscal Research
18 Division, actuary employed by the system or program as to the actuarial effect of the amendment.
19 …
20 (g) In addition to the other requirements of this section, if a bill or resolution adds or
21 modifies service purchase provisions, the Fiscal Research Division actuary employed by the
22 system or program shall obtain provide an estimate of the cost impact of those provisions using
23 the 30-year United States Treasury constant maturity and cost-of-living adjustment and salary
24 increase assumptions consistent with that rate as of December of the year of the most recent
25 actuarial valuation in addition to the cost of the provision using the valuation assumptions."
26
27 GOVOPS MODIFICATIONS
28 SECTION 6.7(a) G.S. 120-14 reads as rewritten:
29 "§ 120-14. Power of committees.
30 Any committee of investigation raised either by joint resolution or resolution of either house
31 of the General Assembly has full power to send for persons and papers, and, if necessary, to
32 compel attendance and production of papers by attachment or otherwise. Except as provided in
33 G.S. 105-259 or when expressly prohibited by federal law, production under this section shall
34 not be denied, delayed, redacted, or otherwise limited. Any confidential information obtained by
35 the Commission shall remain confidential and is not a public record as defined in G.S. 132-1."
36 SECTION 6.7(b) G.S. 120-19 reads as rewritten:
37 "§ 120-19. State officers, etc., upon request, to furnish data and information to legislative
38 committees or commissions.
39 Except as provided in G.S. 105-259, allAll officers, agents, agencies and departments of the
40 State are required to shall give to any committee of either house of the General Assembly, or any
41 committee or commission whose funds are appropriated or transferred to the General Assembly
42 or to the Legislative Services Commission for disbursement, upon request, all information and
43 all data within their possession, accessible or obtainable by them, or ascertainable from their
44 records. This requirement is mandatory and shall include requests made by any individual
45 member of the General Assembly, one of its standing committees or the chair of a standing
46 committee, or any other legislative panel duly appointed by the President Pro Tempore and/or
47 the Speaker of the House or an agent or employee of such a legislative panel.
48 This section supersedes and controls over any conflicting provision of State law other than
49 G.S. 105-259. No officer, agent, agency, or department of the State may deny, delay, redact, or
50 otherwise limit production except to the extent disclosure under this section is expressly
51 prohibited by federal law. Information and data accessible to an officer, agent, agency, or
Page 46 House Bill 1126-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 department includes information and data accessible to a contractor, subcontractor, consultant,
2 vendor, attorney, representative, or other person acting on behalf of the officer, agent, agency, or
3 department. Any confidential information obtained by the Commission shall remain confidential
4 and is not a public record as defined in G.S. 132-1."
5 SECTION 6.7(c) G.S. 120-77 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 120-77. Additional powers; confidentiality; penalties.
7 (a) The Commission shall have the power to compel the following in the discharge of its
8 duties under this Article:
9 (1) Access to any information, data, document or system of record held by a:
10 a. State agency pursuant to the provisions of G.S. 120-19.
11 b. Unit of local government or public authority.
12 c. A non-State entity receiving, directly or indirectly, public funds, to the
13 extent the documents information, data, document, or system of record
14 relate to the receipt, purpose, or implementation of a program or
15 service paid for with public funds.
16 (2) Attendance of any officer or employee officer, employee, agent, contractor,
17 subcontractor, consultant, vendor, grantee, subgrantee, attorney,
18 representative, or other person acting on behalf of any:
19 a. State agency.
20 b. Unit of local government or public authority.
21 c. Non-State entity receiving public funds provided the officer or
22 employee person associated with the entity that is required to attend is
23 responsible for for or has knowledge regarding implementing a
24 program or providing a service paid for with public funds.
25 (a1) This section supersedes and controls over any conflicting provision of State law other
26 than G.S. 105-259. A person or entity subject to this section may not deny, delay, redact, or
27 otherwise limit production of requested material except to the extent disclosure under this section
28 is expressly prohibited by federal law. Requested material accessible to a person or entity subject
29 to this section includes information and data accessible to an officer, employee, agent, contractor,
30 subcontractor, consultant, vendor, grantee, subgrantee, attorney, representative, or other person
31 acting on its behalf.
32 (b) Unless prohibited by federal law, the Commission and Commission staff shall be
33 provided access to all of the following in the discharge of their duties under this Article:
34 (1) Any building or facility allocated to or leased by a State agency.
35 (2) Any building or facility owned or leased by a unit of local government or
36 public authority.
37 (3) Any building or facility owned or leased by a non-State entity receiving public
38 funds provided (i) the building or facility is used to implement a program or
39 provide a service paid for with public funds and (ii) the access is reasonably
40 related to the receipt, purpose, or implementation of a program or service paid
41 for with public funds.
42 (c) The Commission cochairs shall each designate one Commission staff member who
43 shall have access to the BEACON/HR payroll system.
44 (d) Any confidential information obtained by the Commission shall remain confidential
45 and is not a public record as defined in G.S. 132-1.
46 (e) Any document or information obtained or produced by Commission staff in
47 furtherance of staff's duties to the Commission is confidential and is not a public record as defined
48 in G.S. 132-1.
49 (f) Any request made to an agency employee by Commission staff and any
50 communication between Commission staff and an agency employee is confidential. An agency
51 employee shall treat as confidential to a member of Commission staff any request from and any
House Bill 1126-Third Edition Page 47

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 communication with the member. The nature and existence of the request and communications
2 shall only be revealed by an agency employee to another agency employee to the extent that it is
3 necessary to fulfill a request for document production or to gather more information as requested
4 by the member of Commission staff. A violation of this subsection by an agency employee shall
5 be grounds for disciplinary action, including dismissal.
6 (g) A person who conceals, destroys, alters, falsifies, or refuses to provide to the
7 Commission any document, information, data, testimony, system access, or access to any
8 building or facility as required by this Article with the intent to mislead, impede, or interfere with
9 the Commission's discharge of its duties under this Article shall be guilty of a Class 2
10 misdemeanor.
11 (h) The provisions of G.S. 120-19.1 through 120-19.4 shall apply to the proceedings of the
12 Commission as if it were a joint committee of the General Assembly."
