16 ADD CHARTER SCHOOLS AND RELIGIOUS SCHOOLS AS PARTICIPATING
17 INSTITUTIONS
18 SECTION 7.1. G.S. 159D-37 reads as rewritten:
19 "§ 159D-37. Definitions.
20 As used or referred to in this Article, the following words and terms have the following
21 meanings, unless the context clearly indicates otherwise:
22 …
23 (4a) "Institution for elementary and secondary education" means a nonprofit
24 institution within the State of North Carolina authorized by law and engaged
25 or to be engaged in the providing of kindergarten, elementary, or secondary
26 education, or any combination of these.these including, without limitation,
27 charter schools.
28 …
29 (6a) "Project" means any one or more buildings, structures, equipment,
30 improvements, additions, extensions, enlargements, or other facilities
31 comprising any of the following:
32 a. Educational facilities used by an institution for higher education or an
33 institution for elementary and secondary education, including
34 dormitories and other housing facilities, housing facilities for student
35 nurses, dining halls and other food preparation and food service
36 facilities, student unions, administration buildings, academic
37 buildings, libraries, laboratories, research facilities, classrooms,
38 athletic facilities, health care facilities, laundry facilities, and other
39 structures or facilities related to these facilities or required or useful
40 for the instruction of students, the conducting of research, or the
41 operation of the institution.
42 b. Student housing facilities to be owned or operated by an owner or
43 operator other than an institution for higher education or an institution
44 for elementary and secondary education.
45 c. A special purpose project as defined in G.S. 159C-3.
46 The term "project" includes landscaping, site preparation, furniture,
47 equipment and machinery, and other similar items necessary or convenient for
48 operation of a particular facility in the manner for which its use is intended.
49 The term also includes all appurtenances and incidental facilities, such as
50 headquarters or office facilities, maintenance, storage, or utility facilities,
51 parking facilities, and other facilities related to, required, or useful for the
Page 48 House Bill 1126-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 operation of the project or essential or convenient for the orderly conduct of
2 the facility. The term "project" does not include the cost of items that
3 customarily result in a current operating charge, such as books, fuel, or
4 supplies. The term does not include any facility used or to be used for sectarian
5 instruction or as a place of religious worship nor any facility that is used or to
6 be used primarily in connection with any part of the program of a school or
7 department of divinity for any religious denomination.
8 (6b) "Special purpose institution" means a for-profit or not-for-profit corporation
9 or corporation, limited liability company, or similar entity that undertakes any
10 of the activities set forth in sub-subdivisions (6a)b. and (6a)c. subdivision (6a)
11 of this section.
12 …."
13 SECTION 7.2. G.S. 159D-38(a) reads as rewritten:
14 "§ 159D-38. Capital facilities finance agency.
15 (a) There is created a body politic and corporate to be known as "North Carolina Capital
16 Facilities Finance Agency" which shall be constituted a public agency and an instrumentality of
17 the State for the performance of essential public functions. The agency shall be governed by a
18 board of directors composed of seven members. Two of the members of the board shall be the
19 State Treasurer and the State Auditor, both of whom shall serve ex officio. The remaining
20 directors of the agency shall be residents of the State and shall not hold other public office. The
21 General Assembly upon the recommendation of the President Pro Tempore of the Senate shall
22 appoint one director in accordance with G.S. 120-121, the General Assembly upon the
23 recommendation of the Speaker of the House of Representatives shall appoint one director in
24 accordance with G.S. 120-121, and the Governor shall appoint three directors of the agency. The
25 five appointive directors of the agency shall be appointed for staggered four-year terms, two
26 being appointed initially for one year by the President of the Senate and the Speaker of the House,
27 respectively, and one for two years, one for three years and one for four years, respectively, as
28 designated by the Governor. Each director shall continue in office until a successor is duly
29 appointed and qualified, except that any person appointed to fill a vacancy shall serve only for
30 the unexpired term. Any vacancy in a position held by an appointive member shall be filled by a
31 new appointment made by the officer who originally made the appointment. Any member of the
32 board of directors is eligible for reappointment. Each appointive member of the board of directors
33 may be removed by the Governor for misfeasance, malfeasance or neglect of duty after
34 reasonable notice and a public hearing, unless the notice and hearing are in writing expressly
35 waived. Each appointive member of the board of directors shall take an oath of office to
36 administer the duties of office faithfully and impartially and a record of the oath shall be filed in
37 the office of the Secretary of State. The Governor shall designate from among the members of
38 the board of directors a chair and a vice-chair, whose terms extend to the earlier of either two
39 years or the date of expiration of their then current terms as members The State Treasurer shall
40 serve as chair of the board of directors of the agency. The board of directors shall elect and
41 appoint and prescribe the duties of a secretary-treasurer and any other officers it considers
42 necessary or advisable, which officers need not be members of the board of directors."
43
44 MODERNIZE PUBLIC HEARING AND NOTICE REQUIREMENTS
45 SECTION 7.3. G.S. 159D-45 reads as rewritten:
46 "§ 159D-45. Bonds and notes.
47 …
48 (f) Before the issuance of bonds pursuant to this Article to finance a project, the Agency
49 shall hold a public hearing with respect to the proposed project and the issuance of the bonds to
50 finance the proposed project. The public hearing may be held at any location designated by the
51 Agency, including at the offices of the Agency in Raleigh, North Carolina. No public hearing
House Bill 1126-Third Edition Page 49

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 shall be required in connection with the refinancing of any project previously approved by the
2 Agency.
3 The public hearing may be conducted by the Agency or by a hearing officer designated by
4 the Agency to conduct public hearings. Notice of the public hearing must be published at least
5 once in at least one newspaper of general circulation in the county where the proposed project is
6 to be located not less than 14 days before the public hearing. The notice must describe generally
7 the bonds proposed to be issued and the proposed project, including its general location, and any
8 other information the Agency considers appropriate. A copy of the notice of public hearing must
9 be mailed to the clerk of the Board of Commissioners of the county in which the proposed project
10 is to be located and to the governing body of any city or town in which the proposed project is to
11 be operated.shall be consistent with the requirements for reasonable public notice set forth in 26
12 U.S.C. § 147(f) and the regulations promulgated pursuant to that section, or any successor federal
13 provisions or regulations.
14 …."
